  <rdf:Description rdf:about="http://purl.obolibrary.org/obo/GO_0071452">
    <rdf:type rdf:resource="http://www.w3.org/2002/07/owl#Class"/>
    <obo:IAO_0000115>Any process that results in a change in state or activity of a cell (in terms of movement, secretion, enzyme production, gene expression, etc.) as a result of a singlet oxygen stimulus. Singlet oxygen is a dioxygen (O2) molecule in which two 2p electrons have similar spin. Singlet oxygen is more highly reactive than the form in which these electrons are of opposite spin, and it is produced in mutant chloroplasts lacking carotenoids and by leukocytes during metabolic burst.</obo:IAO_0000115>
    <rdfs:label>cellular response to singlet oxygen</rdfs:label>
  </rdf:Description>
